<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="Curr%20Opin%20Ophthalmol"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Towards effective data sharing in ophthalmology: data standardization and data privacy</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Halfpenny%20W"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">William Halfpenny</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3>
<span class="name western">William Halfpenny</span>, <span class="degrees">MEng</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>St. John’s College, Cambridge University, United Kingdom</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Halfpenny%20W"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">William Halfpenny</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Baxter%20SL"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MSc</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Division of Ophthalmology Informatics and Data Science, Viterbi Family Department of Ophthalmology and Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA, USA</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>3</sup>Health Department of Biomedical Informatics, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Baxter%20SL"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>2,</sup><sup>3</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>1</sup>St. John’s College, Cambridge University, United Kingdom</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>2</sup>Division of Ophthalmology Informatics and Data Science, Viterbi Family Department of Ophthalmology and Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA, USA</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>3</sup>Health Department of Biomedical Informatics, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA, USA</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline"><strong>Corresponding Author:</strong> Sally L. Baxter, MD, MSc, Viterbi Family Department of Ophthalmology and Shiley Eye Institute, 9415 Campus Point Dr, MC0946, La Jolla, CA 92093, (858) 246-4604, <span>s1baxter@health.ucsd.edu</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2022 Sep 1.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC9357189  NIHMSID: NIHMS1811594  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35819893/" class="usa-link">35819893</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/ICU.0000000000000878" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Curr Opin Ophthalmol</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="S1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Purpose of the review</h3>
<p id="P1">The purpose of this review is to provide an overview of updates in data standardization and data privacy in ophthalmology. These topics represent two key aspects of medical information sharing and are important knowledge areas given trends in data-driven healthcare.</p></section><section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Recent findings</h3>
<p id="P2">Standardization and privacy can be seen as complementary aspects that pertain to data sharing. Standardization promotes the ease and efficacy through which data is shared. Privacy considerations ensure that data sharing is appropriate and sufficiently controlled. There is active development in both areas, including government regulations and common data models to advance standardization, and application of technologies such as blockchain and synthetic data to help tackle privacy issues. These advancements have seen use in ophthalmology, but there are areas where further work is required.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Summary</h3>
<p id="P3">Information sharing is fundamental to both research and care delivery, and standardization/privacy are key constituent considerations. Therefore, widespread engagement with, and development of, data standardization and privacy ecosystems stand to offer great benefit to ophthalmology.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Privacy, standards, artificial intelligence, interoperability, ophthalmology</p></section></section><section id="S4"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">1. Introduction</h2>
<p id="P4">Data-dependent digital technologies have seen increasing advancement and adoption in recent years in healthcare. Artificial intelligence (AI), for example, is already having an impact across patients, clinicians and health systems[<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>], including in ophthalmology[<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>–<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>].</p>
<p id="P5">Development of digital technologies and clinical information systems typically requires extensive data sharing between entities[<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>]. In AI, this is vital for model performance, and for addressing the issues of generalizability, demographic coverage, and dataset bias. Practical implementation of data sharing requires development of standards for information system interoperability[<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a>].</p>
<p id="P6">Simultaneously, the distribution of medical data raises significant questions about patient data privacy. Privacy is frequently cited as a major concern the public has regarding healthcare data sharing for research[<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a>]. Privacy requirements can also act as an impediment to data use, introducing inefficiencies and disincentivizing research[<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a>]. Methods for maintaining privacy whilst retaining data utility are therefore imperative for AI development in ophthalmology.</p>
<p id="P7">Here we provide an overview of recent articles in both data privacy and data standardization and highlight ongoing efforts to promote data standardization in ophthalmology. <a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a> provides a graphical summary of concepts in this review.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F1"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 1:</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/364e/9357189/ec54d5448ebd/nihms-1811594-f0001.jpg" loading="lazy" height="1246" width="1800" alt="Figure 1:"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P72">High level descriptions of the information management systems that may be seen for two generic data use cases: 1) a clinician accessing a specific patient’s data, and 2) a researcher utilizing multi-site data. This figure highlights where certain standards and privacy technologies would be used. Relevant standards are labeled in red, privacy concepts in blue. Created by <a href="http://BioRender.com" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BioRender.com</a></p></figcaption></figure></section><section id="S5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">2. Data Standardization</h2>
<p id="P8">Standardization refers to agreed-upon methods for connecting systems together and is essential for information exchange[<a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>]. Data standardization is required for the day-to-day operations of information technology (IT) systems, as well as desirable processes such as health data exchange, clinical decision support tool integration, and patient data access[<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a>].</p>
<p id="P9">For these processes to work, standardization may be required at various levels (<a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>), which include the format of the data, communication protocols, definition of minimum required elements, and clinical coding nomenclatures. The following section introduces some of the data standards that are key to ophthalmology, and an overview of recent articles that highlight their application.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T1"><h3 class="obj_head">Table 1.</h3>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P73">Examples of data standards for interoperability in health information technology.</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Standard Category</th>
<th align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Example Standards</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Format or structure of data</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">DICOM - <em>Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine</em><br>OMOP CDM - <em>Observational Medical Outcomes Partnership Common Data Model</em>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Communication protocol</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">FHIR - <em>Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources</em>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Minimum required elements</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">USCDI - <em>United States Core Data for Interoperability</em>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Clinical coding nomenclature</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">ICD-10 - <em>International Classification of Diseases, Tenth Revision</em>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><section id="S6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.1. Data models</h3>
<p id="P10">A data model describes the logical structure of information within a database. Documentation and understanding of this model are required for performing actions, such as inputting data or performing queries. Database structure is often unique to specific implementations: differing, for example, between electronic health records (EHRs) designed by different manufacturers. This causes issues when researchers wish to collate and analyze data from diverse sources, as it requires significant effort to aggregate the data and write customized search queries.</p>
<p id="P11">Database standards mitigate this problem by allowing data from disparate sources to be harmonized. A prominent example of this is the Observational Medical Outcomes Partnership Common Data Model (OMOP CDM)[<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a>]. Harmonizing healthcare data into this format facilitates analysis and model training and enables comparisons of results across different institutions or settings.</p>
<p id="P12">There are already examples where the OMOP CDM has been used for clinical benefit in ophthalmology. Mun et al. used OMOP CDM databases to estimate the incidence of endophthalmitis after intravitreal anti-VEGF injections[<a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a>]. From a database of 8 million patients across 3 hospitals, they identified 23,490 patients who had received anti-VEGF injections with data available to analyze. OMOP enabled integration across multiple sources and allowed standardized querying.</p>
<p id="P13">The American Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) has advocated for data standardization in ophthalmology for several decades, and recently has become increasingly active via a Standards Workgroup that includes clinicians and members from academia, industry, and governmental entities such as the National Eye Institute (NEI). This group, alongside an AAO task force on leveraging data for understanding eye care disparities, have prepared a white paper which discusses the potential for improved understanding of health disparities by integrating ophthalmology data with large cross-specialty datasets that are already mapped to OMOP. One example is the National Institutes of Health (NIH) <em>All of Us</em> Research Program, which is attempting to build a diverse dataset from the voluntary information of 1 million people across the US[<a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>]. The AAO Standards Workgroup was recently approved to establish a new OMOP Work Group in Eye Care and Vision Research, which welcomes ophthalmologists, optometrists, and vision researchers to contribute to advancing a common data model for ophthalmology.</p></section><section id="S7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.2. Law in healthcare standards: Cures Act Final Rule</h3>
<p id="P14">Standardization is more impactful when it is widely used. Consequently, regulatory bodies will often mandate the use of certain standards within the healthcare system. A recent example of this in the United States has been the introduction of the 21st Century Cures Act Final Rule (“Final Rule”)[<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>], which was signed into law in 2016 but continues to come into effect until the end of 2023. A target of this rule was to improve interoperability, and, alongside prohibition of information blocking, it made several provisions relating to the USCDI and FHIR data standards.</p>
<section id="S8"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">2.2.1. USCDI</h4>
<p id="P15">One standard mentioned in the Final Rule was the United States Core Data for Interoperability (USCDI). USCDI is ‘a standardized set of health data classes and constituent data elements for nationwide, interoperable health information exchange’[<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>]. It enumerates the data elements that Health IT providers must make available. Engagement with this standard could be important for ophthalmology, as it may provide opportunities for improved data collection, such as for public health monitoring, and better health information exchange.</p>
<p id="P16">The Office of the National Coordinator (ONC) has emphasized that the USCDI is to be continually improved via a collaborative process involving feedback from multiple stakeholders[<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>]. There is ongoing work to advocate for alignment with the needs of ophthalmology. The NEI has submitted public comments to support the addition of ophthalmic data elements (refraction, visual acuity, and intraocular pressure) to the USCDI. The AAO Standards Workgroup also contends that including ocular data elements in the USCDI standard would have widespread benefit. In diabetes management, for example, including ocular data elements would facilitate cooperation between multiple medical specialties, and facilitate public health monitoring of diabetic vision status, which is a key measure of care performance.</p>
<p id="P17">Inclusion of visual acuity in USCDI could also help monitor compliance of processes like pediatric visual screening, which is mandated under the Affordable Care Act. Given that decreased visual acuity can enable children to access additional education and social support services, such an implementation has consequences outside of medicine alone. It is hoped that including eye metrics in USCDI would emphasize its importance to care providers in general.</p></section><section id="S9"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">2.2.2. FHIR</h4>
<p id="P18">As part of the Final Rule, it was also mandated that all health IT providers should provide application programming interfaces (APIs) for health data exchange and that these APIs should conform to the FHIR standard[<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>]. FHIR is the communications standard, developed by HL7, for exchanging healthcare information electronically[<a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a>], and the ONC-mandated deadline for its implementation is 12/31/2022[<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>].</p>
<p id="P19">One barrier with FHIR is that there has been no implementation guide for the practical application of FHIR to ophthalmology. This problem has been identified by the “Eyes of FHIR” initiative[<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>], which aims to represent the comprehensive ophthalmic clinical lexicon in FHIR format. In 2021, an event run by this initiative showcased a bidirectional real-time data exchange between diagnostic devices, EHR and PACS systems, in a world first proof-of-concept[<a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>].</p></section></section><section id="S10"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.3. Imaging standards: DICOM</h3>
<p id="P20">Imaging is an important part of modern ophthalmology practice and is an area where ophthalmology has become a forerunner in AI. The application of deep learning to automated image-based diagnosis of diabetic retinopathy, for example, was one of the first healthcare AI algorithms to receive FDA approval and see clinical use[<a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>,<a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a>].</p>
<p id="P21">Across most other medical fields, there is a well-established imaging standard, DICOM[<a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a>]. Uptake of DICOM in ophthalmology, however, is currently poor compared to other imaging-centric fields, despite the development of necessary standards[<a href="#R28" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R28">28</a>,<a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a>]. In 2021, the AAO made a public call, subsequently echoed worldwide, for ophthalmic imaging device manufacturers to ensure they comply with DICOM[<a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">19</a>,<a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a>]. A common issue is the practice of only making ophthalmology image data available in a manufacturer-specific viewer or exported PDF. This stops access to structured, usable data, preventing interoperability with other information management systems. Even when DICOM standards are implemented, ophthalmic manufacturers often do not use the most data-rich formats.</p>
<p id="P22">Widespread DICOM uptake could have many benefits, allowing researchers to pool data from disparate sources and facilitating the development of device-agnostic AI models. It would also open the possibility for centralized synthesis of imaging and EHR data within a hospital. There do exist barriers to DICOM, however. For vendors, the reasons cited include high costs and insufficient user demand. Clinician worries include compatibility of legacy data, availability of manufacturer-specific support tools and further costs.</p>
<p id="P23">In lieu of inbuilt interoperability, researchers have found ways of extracting standardized information from manufacturer-formatted output. Saifee et al.[<a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>] developed software for extracting and structuring metadata, value plot data and percentile plot data from Humphrey visual field reports. Similarly, Mun et al.[<a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a>] developed a system for extracting relevant data from optical coherence tomography (OCT) images and further transformed the data into the OMOP Common Data Format (see <a href="#S6" class="usa-link">section 2.1</a>).</p></section></section><section id="S11"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">3. Data privacy</h2>
<p id="P24">Broadly speaking, the topic of data privacy is concerned with ensuring that information is not accessed erroneously, although a precise definition is notoriously difficult[<a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a>]. Cohen and Price[<a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a>] posit that the propriety of information sharing depends on the actors involved, the process by which information is accessed, the frequency of access and the purpose of access.</p>
<p id="P25">Data privacy presents challenges in the ethical, legal and technological domains. The following section will predominantly discuss global developments in the technological aspects, but readers should be aware that the field extends beyond this.</p>
<section id="S12"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1. Blockchain</h3>
<p id="P26">Interest in using blockchain in medicine has grown over the past few years[<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a>]. At its core, the blockchain paradigm provides a way to have a decentralized database where 1) the contents are universally agreed upon, and 2) data cannot be removed/changed once it has been added[<a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25</a>]. In a review by Hasselgren et al.[<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a>], the most common problem solved by blockchain, and one that is relevant to data privacy, was the management of access control.</p>
<p id="P27">Whilst it may not be accessible for everyone to understand the underpinnings of blockchain, it is important to be aware of its promises and limitations. The use of blockchain does not, inherently, confer data privacy: unencrypted health records placed on a public blockchain, for example, would be observable by everyone. However, as a result of its decentralization and immutability, it does provide some useful features: tolerance to loss/corruption, availability, transparency, trust and verifiability[<a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">26</a>]. These are useful features for managing access to data.</p>
<p id="P28">A paper by Tan et al.[<a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">27</a>] gives an example of how such a system may work for ophthalmology. These researchers used a consortium blockchain shared between research sites to coordinate the training of deep learning models and data sharing, for the purpose of detecting myopic macular degeneration and high myopia from retinal images. The blockchain was used to record what data and models an institution had available, to grant and log access to these assets, and to record the performance of the models. Access could then be granted by sharing of keys that allowed users to download and decrypt data via alternative routes. Finally, model performance metrics were stored on-chain. The authors suggested that blockchain provides a more automated approach for providing transaction history and preventing inconsistencies, as well as preventing tampering of historical evidence.</p>
<p id="P29">One drawback of using blockchain for access control, exemplified by this work, is that although it allows secure access management, approved users still need to download or view data in some form. This takes the data outside the data custodian’s sphere of control, meaning privacy is dependent on interparty trust. The approaches discussed next offer a solution to this problem. For a more comprehensive overview of blockchain in ophthalmology, readers are directed to a review by Ng et al.[<a href="#R28" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R28">28</a>].</p></section><section id="S13"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.2. Federated analysis</h3>
<p id="P30">The classical first step in a data analysis or machine learning workflow is the collection of all relevant data at a central location, such as a local server or cloud platform. Recently, however, this workflow paradigm has been challenged with the concept of federated analysis/federated machine learning[<a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a>]. In federated approaches, instead of sending the data to the central site, the analysis code is sent to the data sites, whereupon each site executes the analysis against its own database and feeds back the outcome for aggregation at the central site.</p>
<p id="P31">The advantage of this approach is clear: data stays within the walls of the institution holding it. This helps institutions maintain agency over the data for which they are responsible. Research has shown that performance of algorithms trained with a federated approach can often approach that of centrally-trained algorithms[<a href="#R30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R30">30</a>].</p>
<p id="P32">Examples of federated learning being applied to ophthalmology have appeared in recent years. Mehta et al.[<a href="#R31" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R31">31</a>] demonstrated the training of a model that could detect intraretinal fluid on OCT B-scans using a model-to-data approach, sending a pre-trained model along with retraining code to the data site. Subsequently, Lo et al.[<a href="#R32" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R32">32</a>] used a federated machine learning approach for automated microvasculature segmentation of OCTA en face images, as well as for referable diabetic retinopathy classification, demonstrating good performance in both tasks.</p>
<p id="P33">Another example is currently being undertaken by an American Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) task force on leveraging data for health inequalities, where they are investigating a federated approach to widen access to the AAO Intelligent Research in Sight (IRIS) Registry. As a test case, they are analyzing disparities among patients with diabetic retinopathy requiring surgical intervention by containerizing scripts in Docker containers that are applied to the IRIS Registry data to execute analyses without requiring direct data access.</p></section><section id="S14"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.3. Synthetic data</h3>
<p id="P34">Synthetic data generation is a process used to extract useful information from real-world patient data, and re-express this through artificial data sets[<a href="#R33" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R33">33</a>]. In healthcare, the typical goal is generation of new patient data that, when analyzed or used for model training, gives similar outputs to what would have been achieved with the source data. Because no actual patient information is shared, this process allows privacy-preserving distribution of useful data content[<a href="#R34" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R34">34</a>].</p>
<p id="P35">Synthetic data generation methods can involve domain knowledge and modeling, or data-driven generative techniques. Synthetic models have been created for a variety of cases across healthcare, including EHRs[<a href="#R35" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R35">35</a>,<a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">36</a>] and Internet of Things (IoT)-derived data[<a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">37</a>], Synthea being one notable example[<a href="#R38" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R38">38</a>,<a href="#R39" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R39">39</a>]. In ophthalmology, Abdelmotaal et al. recently demonstrated the ability of a generative adversarial network (GAN) to create plausible Scheimplfug camera tomography images. They then demonstrated that these synthetic images could be used to train a deep learning model that subsequently performed well on real images[<a href="#R40" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R40">40</a>].</p>
<p id="P36">Wang et al. provided a review of the use of GANs for image synthesis in ophthalmology, highlighting the use of this approach in the generation of fundus images and optical coherence tomography[<a href="#R41" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R41">41</a>]. Fundal images present a particular issue for data privacy because retinal vasculature is uniquely identifiable, and can be used for biometric identification[<a href="#R42" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R42">42</a>]. Currently, the “expert determination” method allows fundal images to be classed as de-identified under HIPAA[<a href="#R43" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R43">43</a>], but the validity of this is disputed, with some arguing that such biometric identification may be even more sensitive than other protected health information due to its unalterable nature[<a href="#R42" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R42">42</a>]. Synthetic generation methods may therefore become crucial for such cases.</p>
<p id="P37">In contrast to previously discussed methods, synthetic data has the advantage that patient confidentiality stays intact even in the case of data breaches, as even the full dataset has no determinable mapping to real patients[<a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">36</a>,<a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">37</a>]. Researchers have also suggested that synthetic data generation techniques could provide a cheaper alternative to traditional data anonymization techniques[<a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">36</a>]. Synthetic data may offer benefits additional to preserving patient privacy, as evidenced by the work of Burlina et al., where synthetic datasets were used to debiase retinal diagnostic algorithms[<a href="#R44" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R44">44</a>].</p></section><section id="S15"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.4. Differential Privacy</h3>
<p id="P38">Our intuition about whether information disclosures maintain privacy are often incorrect. The strategy of removing “identifiable” information, for example, can be undermined through linkage attacks[<a href="#R45" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R45">45</a>]. Similarly, publications of summary statistics for a cohort can be used to re-identify individuals, as described by the Fundamental Law of Information Recovery[<a href="#R46" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R46">46</a>]. To quote the originators of this law, “Overly accurate answers to too many questions will destroy privacy in a spectacular way.”</p>
<p id="P39">This problem is addressed through a mathematical definition of privacy, known as differential privacy. Differential privacy is a property of a system that discloses information about a database. It defines a limit on how much privacy any individual loses when the system is used. Differentially private algorithms are those designed with this property in mind, and they achieve differential privacy by incorporating some noise in their query responses.</p>
<p id="P40">In contrast to other approaches discussed, differential privacy is a more fundamental quality. The rigorous constraints of differentially private algorithms mean that they give provable levels of protection against arbitrary risks/attacks, regardless of method. The strategy also permits quantification of privacy loss, which could give participants a measure of worst-case privacy risks and allow tracking of privacy loss over time. The trade-off is that differential privacy requires addition of noise, and therefore has to impart some amount of inaccuracy to any results.</p>
<p id="P41">Although differential privacy is being applied to the healthcare space, real-world implementations are scant[<a href="#R47" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R47">47</a>]. We are not aware of any implementations in the ophthalmology space, although feasibility has been demonstrated for other imaging[<a href="#R48" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R48">48</a>].</p></section></section><section id="S16"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">4. Conclusion</h2>
<p id="P42">Data sharing is becoming increasingly important for ophthalmology, and healthcare more widely. The interoperability and security of our information systems is crucial. To advance interoperability, awareness and implementation of current standards is needed, as are efforts to expand standards for ophthalmic data to address gaps in current standards. Advances in data privacy will also be critical as data sharing becomes more widespread. Although there will always be a tension between confidentiality and data sharing, improved efficacy in ensuring the former holds promise for facilitating the latter.</p></section><section id="floats-group1" class="floats-group"><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX1"><h2 class="obj_head">Key Points.</h2>
<ul id="L2" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P74">Data standardization and data privacy are both necessary for effective clinical information exchange.</p></li>
<li><p id="P75">There is ongoing work to improve technology in these areas, and to trial their application in ophthalmology.</p></li>
<li><p id="P76">Both clinicians and researchers stand to gain from contributing and engaging with these endeavors.</p></li>
</ul></section></section><section id="S17" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Acknowledgements</h2>
<section id="S18"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Financial support and sponsorship:</h3>
